Citation.sTitle: Effects of Concentration, Temperature, and Solvent Composition on the Partial Molar Volumes of Sodium Lauryl Sulfate in Methanol (1) + Water (2) Mixed Solvent Media
Citation.sAbstract: Precise measurements on the density of sodium lauryl sulfate in pure water and in methanol (1) + water (2) mixed  solvent media containing (0.10, 0.20, 0.30, and 0.40) volume fractions of methanol at (298.15, 308.15, 318.15, and 323.15) K are  reported. The concentrations are varied from (0.3 3 10 1 to 1.3 3 10 1) mol 3 kg 1. The results were almost constant on the partial  molar volumes with increasing surfactant concentration. Also, the partial molar volumes are found to increase with increasing  temperature over the entire concentration range investigated in a given mixed solvent medium and are found to decrease with  increasing methanol content in the solvent composition.
